00:00:20.940 --> 00:00:26.240
So we'll be taking a look at what direct lighting versus indirect lighting and shadows are.

6
00:00:26.240 --> 00:00:32.000
So in this case, direct lighting is the light that goes directly from the light source onto

7
00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:36.400
the surface without any interference, which means that it receives the full spectrum of

8
00:00:36.400 --> 00:00:39.720
the light in terms of color.

9
00:00:39.720 --> 00:00:42.160
Now indirect lighting is slightly different to that.

10
00:00:42.160 --> 00:00:46.800
It's when lighting's been bounced off a surface and lights another object.

11
00:00:46.800 --> 00:00:52.640
Now when lighting hits that surface, that surface absorbs some of the light and the

12
00:00:52.640 --> 00:00:55.680
light that gets bounced out is actually tinted.

13
00:00:55.680 --> 00:01:01.680
So indirect lighting contributes to the overall mood and light intensity of the scene and

14
00:01:01.680 --> 00:01:03.720
color as well.

15
00:01:03.720 --> 00:01:09.480
And then the shadows are important to understand that it's essentially a real engine takes

16
00:01:09.480 --> 00:01:15.400
a snapshot of a mesh from the light's point of view and projects the shadow information

17
00:01:15.400 --> 00:01:17.840
onto another surface from that point of view.

18
00:01:17.840 --> 00:01:22.560
So as long as we're all agreed on this, I think as I start talking about these concepts

